One-to-One Relationship (JPA / Database)
1. Confirming One-to-One in the Database

For a true one-to-one relationship, one table must store a unique identifier of the other table, usually the primary key.

2. Ensuring Uniqueness

The join column in the owning side must use unique = true.
This prevents duplicate foreign key values.
Without this uniqueness, the relationship would behave like one-to-many or many-to-one (e.g., Person–Passport example).


mappedBy

Indicates that the relationship already exists, and this side is just referencing it.
If mappedBy is NOT used in a bidirectional relationship, JPA will create a third join table with both primary keys.
mappedBy is always used on the non-owning (inverse) side.


Owning vs Non-Owning Side

Owning side → The table that contains the foreign key.
Non-owning (inverse) side → Does not store the foreign key; depends on mappedBy.


Bidirectional vs Unidirectional

Bidirectional:

Navigation possible from both entities.
Example: Person ↔ Passport.


Unidirectional:

Only one entity can access the other.




Owning Side Impact

The owning side decides the database updates (inserts, updates of foreign key).


Cascade Types

PERSIST → Saving parent also saves child.
MERGE → Updating parent also updates child.
REMOVE → Deleting parent deletes child.
REFRESH → Reloading parent reloads child from DB.
DETACH → Detaching parent detaches child from persistence context.
ALL → Applies all the above.


JSON Handling

Use @JsonIgnore on the inverse (non-owning) side to prevent infinite recursion during JSON serialization.

